mated_tokens":2653,"estimated_tokens_delta":16,"uuid":"6fe3b908-4b95-4138-80bd-5283cec2d8fa","session_id":"1c4ddf8f-f83d-4284-a03e-d15626d7227f"},{"type":"system","subtype":"thinking_tokens","estimated_tokens":2664,"estimated_tokens_delta":11,"uuid":"f2937536-2991-4af3-8bbf-f456045fe03d","session_id":"1c4ddf8f-f83d-4284-a03e-d15626d7227f"},{"type":"system","subtype":"thinking_tokens","estimated_tokens":11336,"estimated_tokens_delta":8672,"uuid":"a76b8b71-49de-49cb-bea1-a58c8b91fbda","session_id":"1c4ddf8f-f83d-4284-a03e-d15626d7227f"},{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01JqDDQ5oZjGpc3ydKyHbyot","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of what I need to implement. Let me plan the implementation:\n\n1. `word_garden/__init__.py` - empty package init\n2. `word_garden/words.py` - WORDS list, select_word(), water_for()\n3. `word_garden/game.py` - GameState dataclass, new_game(), validate_guess(), apply_guess(), display_word(), is_won(), is_lost()\n4. `tests/__init__.py` - empty\n5. `tests/test_game.py` - tests for game logic\n6. `tests/test_words.py` - tests for words module\n7. Looking at the spec details: difficulty tiers map to water amounts and word lengths, the word list has ten specific words, and GameState needs to track the secret word, guessed letters, remaining water, weed count, max water, plus status messaging and game state flags.\n\nNow I'm checking the word lengths against the difficulty requirements—most words fit the Easy category (4-6 letters), while longer words like TERMINAL, VINEYARD, and SEEDLING qualify for Normal difficulty, and ORCHARD and HARVEST work for Hard mode.\n\nI'll define message constants in game.py to follow the best practice of storing user-facing strings in one place, then I'm ready to build out the module structure starting with words.py.\n\nNow I'm setting up the words list and difficulty configuration, with a function to retrieve water amounts for each difficulty level and another to select a random word based on difficulty constraints. Defining game messages and the GameState dataclass to track the current game, then setting up the new_game function to initialize a fresh game with a selected word.\n\nNow I'm writing the validation logic to check that a guess is a single letter, and the apply_guess function to process the player's guess against the game state. Now I'm thinking through the `apply_guess` method logic: if the game's already over, it should be a no-op with a message; if the letter was already guessed, no state changes but return a message; correct guesses add to the set and check for a win condition; incorrect guesses decrement water, increment weeds, and check for a loss. I'll use `dataclasses.replace()` to create new GameState instances rather than mutating the existing one, keeping things functional. I'm also refining the message constants based on the spec—correct guesses say \"Good guess! The garden grows,\" incorrect ones say \"No match. A weed appears,\" repeated guesses include the dynamic letter in the message, and win/loss messages follow the specified format. I'll consolidate the invalid input messages into a single constant since they share the same text, but keep them as separate constants in case the behavior diverges later. The Code Tips remind me that all user-facing strings should live in game.py as module-level constants, which the tests will import directly rather than duplicating literals. For `display_word`, I need to format it with spaces between letters and underscores for unguessed positions. Now I'm ready to structure the implementation files, using immutable state updates with `dataclasses.replace()` for `apply_guess`.\n\nImplementing apply_guess logic... Checking the game-over logic more carefully—when a wrong guess brings water to zero, `is_lost` correctly returns true since it checks that water is depleted and the word isn't fully guessed yet. The key thing is that `is_lost` evaluates the state *after* the guess is applied, so if water hits zero on a wrong guess, the game ends as a loss before any subsequent correct guesses could happen. When water hits zero after a wrong guess, the new state triggers `is_lost` to return True since the water condition is met and the word isn't fully guessed yet, which sets `game_over`. I'm thinking of `is_lost` as a pure predicate that just checks the water condition regardless of the `game_over` flag—this keeps it simple for both internal use in `apply_guess` and for external callers querying the game state.\n\nFor the loss condition specifically, I need to verify that water at zero counts as a loss only if the word hasn't been won yet, so using `is_won(state)` inside `is_lost` makes sense to avoid circular logic. Now I'm moving on to the test cases from the spec—I need to cover scenarios like correct guesses revealing letters, incorrect guesses reducing water and increasing weeds, and so on through all ten cases.\n\nThe testing approach is to construct GameState objects directly with known values rather than relying on randomness, and to assert the full observable outcome of each state transition across all affected fields. I'm setting up the test file structure and importing the necessary functions and classes.\n\nWriting test cases... Adding more test cases... Adding more test cases... Writing test cases...\n\nI'm also thinking through what else needs testing—making sure the game state doesn't get mutated unexpectedly, handling edge cases like guessing after the game ends, and validating that invalid difficulty levels raise errors. I should verify that `new_game` initializes everything correctly and that the win/loss detection works at the boundaries. Since I'm using set operations like `state.guessed_letters | {letter}` to create new sets rather than mutating the original, the immutability should be preserved.\n\nFor the post-game behavior, when the game is already over, applying another guess just updates the status message while keeping everything else intact—a no-op that still provides feedback. I also need to make sure the word display function correctly shows revealed letters and blanks based on what's been guessed. One important constraint from the code tips: if a function accepts an `rng` parameter that defaults to `None`, I need to use the module-level random functions rather than creating a fresh seeded instance internally.\n\nIn `select_word`, I'm checking whether the filtered word pool is empty and raising a `ValueError` if no words match the difficulty level, rather than silently falling back to an unfiltered set. I also need to handle the `rng` parameter correctly—using it if provided, otherwise falling back to the module-level random choice.\n\nLooking at the repo structure, there's no existing `src` directory yet, just the spec and task files, so I'll need to create the project structure from scratch. Looking at the spec examples for win/loss screens, I need to define message templates that will be formatted with the guessed word. I'll create template strings for both outcomes and use them in the guess logic, then write out all the module files cleanly using dataclasses utilities.\n\nNow I'm setting up the words module with a word list, difficulty configuration that maps each level to water count and word length constraints, and helper functions to retrieve water amounts and select words based on difficulty.\n\nI'm also starting the game module with message constants for game feedback. Finishing the GameState initialization with the word and water values, then defining a validation function that checks the input is a single letter, and starting to implement the guess application logic that handles game-over states and duplicate guesses. Writing game logic... Adding test cases... Writing test file... Adding test cases... Adding more test cases... Writing test cases... Adding test cases... Now I'm testing the display_word function to ensure it properly masks unguessed letters with blanks and reveals guessed ones in their correct positions, checking cases where no letters are guessed, some are guessed, and all letters are guessed.\n\nI'm moving on to test the win and loss conditions—verifying that is_won returns false when the word is incomplete and true when all letters are guessed, and checking that is_lost correctly identifies when the player has run out of water. Checking word length distributions across difficulty tiers...\n\nNow I'm considering whether to use `from __future__ import annotations` for the game module. Since Python 3.10+ natively supports type hints like `set[str]` and `tuple[str | None, str]` at runtime, I don't need the future import. For `guessed_letters` in `GameState`, the task specifies `set[str]`, so I'll stick with that, though I need to think through how `dataclasses.replace()` handles creating new set references.\n\nI should verify that the original state's `guessed_letters` set isn't mutated when I create a new game state. My approach uses set union (`state.guessed_letters | {letter}`) which creates a fresh set, preserving the original. Let me trace through some edge cases for `validate_guess`: whitespace gets stripped, then the result is checked for length and alphabetic characters. So `\" a \"` becomes `\"A\"` (valid), `\"ab\"` stays two characters (invalid), and `\"1\"` fails the alphabetic check. Non-alphabetic characters like digits and punctuation remain non-alpha even after calling `upper()`.\n\nNow I'm thinking about how to organize the difficulty configuration constants in a clean, readable structure, and I need to make sure the `__init__.py` files exist in both the package and tests directories. I should also add a `.gitignore` to exclude Python cache files.\n\nBefore I start writing the actual code, I need to reconsider the message constants strategy—the guidelines emphasize defining user-facing strings once at the module level so tests can import and reuse them rather than duplicating literals. When testing something like a repeated guess, I'll import the template constant and format it with the specific letter to verify the exact message the user sees.\n\nI should also double-check the directory structure since there's no `word_garden/` or `tests/` directory yet, and I want to confirm whether `.gitignore` exists before proceeding. For the validation messages, I need to decide if `MSG_INVALID_EMPTY` and `MSG_INVALID_MULTI` should be distinct constants even though the spec shows the same text for both—the task description suggests each error should have its own specific, helpful message. I'll use a single constant `MSG_INVALID_NOT_SINGLE` for both empty and multi-character inputs since they share the same message, keeping the code cleaner and making the intent clearer. Then I'm setting up the test imports to reference these message constants. Defining the error message constants... A single emoji like \"🌱\" counts as one character in Python, so it would fail the alpha check and return MSG_INVALID_NOT_LETTER. I'm ready to write the validation code now.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4382,"cache_read_input_tokens":25547,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4382},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1c4ddf8f-f83d-4284-a03e-d15626d7227f","uuid":"a0d33597-5034-4a94-a74e-31725ad9949b","request_id":"req_011CbxeyS3xQLuMYb2c4yvto"},{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01JqDDQ5oZjGpc3ydKyHbyot","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Let me check the .gitignore and farnsworth.json before creating files."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"